Here's a quick test:

``` javascript
var express = require('express')
  , http = require('http')

var app = express()
  , port = 3001;

app.use(app.router);

app.get('/*.html', function(req, res, next) {
  res.send(req.path);
});

http.createServer(app).listen(port, function() {
  console.log('Express server listening on port %d', port);
});
```
- `/works.html` works fine
- `/%doesntwork.html` fails with  the following:

  ```
  URIError: URI malformed
  at decodeURIComponent (native)

  at Route.match (/Users/lxe/devel/node_modules/express/lib/router/route.js:61:9)
  ```

Looks as though `/*.html` becomes this regex `/^\/(.*)\.html\/?$/i`. (I'm not quite sure at which step at this point.) 

`route.js` then calls decodeURIcomponent (https://github.com/visionmedia/express/blob/master/lib/router/route.js#L61) on that capture group, which has a spurious '%' character, which causes it to fail.

Explicitly removing the capture group, and just defining your route with a regex `app.get(/^\/.*\.html\/?$/i, ...)` fixes that, but I wonder if that deodeURIcomponent is really necessary there.

Connect's `lib/proto.js`, which provides the `requestListener` (`exports.handle` in `proto.js`) used by Express and Connect apps, uses `process.env.NODE_ENV`:

```
// Connect: lib/proto.js
var env = process.env.NODE_ENV || 'development';

app.handle = function(req, res, out) {
[code]
  var msg = 'production' == env
          ? http.STATUS_CODES[res.statusCode]
          : err.stack || err.toString();
[code]
})
```

Wouldn't it be better to have all `env` decisions based on the same source? If so, how could this be done? On one hand, setting `process.env.NODE_ENV` in Express's `app.set('env', $environment_string)` is kinda gross. On the other hand, changing Connect doesn't seem to be the way to go either.

