`connect#createServer()` lets you register middleware upon app creation by passing them as arguments to `connect#createServer()`.

In `express.js`, we have the `createApplication()` app "constructor":

```
function createApplication() {
  var app = connect();
  utils.merge(app, proto);
  app.request = { __proto__: req, app: app };
  app.response = { __proto__: res, app: app };
  app.init();
  return app;
}
```

The first thing this does is create a connect app:

```
var app = connect();
```

Which calls `connect#createServer()` in `connect.js` This function lets you pass middleware as arguments (see the `for` loop, which registers each argument):

```
function createServer() {
  function app(req, res, next){ app.handle(req, res, next); }
  utils.merge(app, proto);
  utils.merge(app, EventEmitter.prototype);
  app.route = '/';
  app.stack = [];
  for (var i = 0; i < arguments.length; ++i) {
    app.use(arguments[i]);
  }
  return app;
};
```

Since `express#createApplication()` doesn't use its arguments, why not just pass them through to the `connect()` call? Or, is there some future design in mind that will use them?

